<subSubSection id="A82B60AE2BB7639740B3CA89CDA29ABD" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="type">
<paragraph id="B6BA9A01C358428885682401BA05C4CF" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0430C59582D1205833D52DA91AC9B1CE" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
TURKEY, Eski-Scheher, 
<emphasis id="EA267722BC8D1BDA811D2CCD289B6103" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Warburg &amp; Endlich</emphasis>
515 (holotype B!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="595540726D990386D0DEB61055DEB1D4" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="description">
<paragraph id="A2F08ACA118062F75AECAFF7B61ED9E1" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C1B8BCE21E16F33B186BE0CE91F45B76" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Compact cushion-forming undershrub with thick woody taproot, branched at base with short woody prostrate to ascending branches to c. 15 cm, young stems sericeous. Leaves sessile, 1.2-2 
<normalizedToken id="87360798CCABBA6822E1F98DEC0F1820" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.4 cm, linear-oblanceolate, acute, attenuate at the base, sericeous and with some spreading hairs. Flowers solitary, axillary, shortly pedunculate but becoming crowded, sessile and subcapitate towards the branch tips; peduncles 0-5 mm, pilose; bracts leaf-like; bracteoles similar but shorter; sepals 8-11 
<normalizedToken id="A182E26C4DE3F73892219BCD7CDD4EC1" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3 mm, oblong, acute to apiculate, concave, adpressed pilose, not bicoloured; corolla 1.7-2.3 cm long, white with distinct pink, pubescent midpetaline bands, unlobed; ovary pilose; style glabrous, divided c. 4 mm above base; stigmas 4 mm. Capsule and seeds unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F9FF39CA5EBADC46D078CEC714F3364F" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9C05443714C3E72B1507EC84557F91D8" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F069F906F92F59EFC0C2677D50B90D74" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Endemic to Turkey (
<emphasis id="DA9A6301F9C3B70D0EF870D7D6D9387E" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Rechinger</emphasis>
61014, 
<emphasis id="897B2133D227040FB6F484ABCE9D70FC" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Fitz &amp; Spitzenberger</emphasis>
721, 
<emphasis id="A2B138456FBE8BCE8C4C06E0A8AE8D43" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Sorger</emphasis>
s.n. [28/5/1964]).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B1426EC965444A3405F487F9561B41FE" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="notes">
<paragraph id="44880364915E50A1B6322791974D2B61" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1896A32B81BB7B3C2DBCD560031ABD6E" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Could be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="D59445C30A6FC0E1FC93A501B7D52493" authorityName="Stace, Bot. J. Linn. Soc. 64: 58. 1971. (Stace" authorityYear="1971" baseAuthorityName="Boiss." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus boissieri subsp. compactus" order="Solanales" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="boissieri" subSpecies="compactus">Convolvulus boissieri subsp. compactus</taxonomicName>
but the 1-nerved, near linear leaves are distinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="27F70E7D296C336F032E91353C539F61" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Although 
<bibRefCitation id="6AF8E22CF32C389BFD4F131174C6E2D3" author="Parris, BS" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Turkey" pageId="208" pageNumber="209" pagination="198 - 219" refId="B256" refString="Parris, BS, 1978. Convolvulus. Flora of Turkey volume 6: 198 - 219" title="Convolvulus." volume="volume 6" year="1978">Parris (1978</bibRefCitation>
: 209) treated 
<taxonomicName id="70F003CC6662A336CBB6CFEE32B042D0" authorityName="Bornm., Repert Spec. Nov. Regni Veg. 5: 168. 1908. (Bornmueller" authorityYear="1908" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus phrygius" order="Solanales" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="phrygius">
<emphasis id="14C37DCD0FD7BF39C50C43932B6EF370" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Convolvulus phrygius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5EFAC71E094D08F4C2C6569AE29F3018" authorityName="Sa'ad" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus pulvinatus" order="Solanales" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pulvinatus">
<emphasis id="914FCA77C25428420BCF542630CDAFB7" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Convolvulus pulvinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as distinct species, they were collected at the same place and the distinctions in measurements are minor. The corollas are similar in size and the sepals are only about 2 mm different in length. There is no good reason to treat them as separate species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
